1.
    a.
        Because deep sea fishing involves going very far from land, where the fisher may become susceptible to storms, large waves, faulty equipment, etc while being far enough away that it is difficult for help to arrive
    b.
        1.
            Because storms or other natural disasters could kill off or otherwise destroy offshore fish farms, which would need time to recover. This would change how much fish can be produced.
        2.
            Because it is not possible to say for certain the amount of new fish sired by each mother, and the rate of survival of those fishes, which will change how much fish can be produced
        3.
            Because unpredictable economic pressures may cause differing levels of investment into smart fish farming at sea, which will change how much fish can be produced.
    c.
        Fish farms cause pollution as they concentrate large amounts of fish in a single area, which secrete waste, which can pollute the environment; also, because fish farms use large amounts of growth stimulants, antibiotics, and pesticides to increase yield, which may diffuse out of the fish farm, polluting the environment. The aforementioned may cause issues such as eutrophication or antibiotic resistance in bacteria.
    d.
        i.
            The fish farmer could apply large amounts of antibiotics and pesticides into the water in their fish-farm to kill bacteria and disease-spreading pests in the fish farm to reduce the incidence of disease in a fish farm.
        ii.
            Large amounts of antibiotics could cause bacterial resistance to antibiotics and large amounts of pesticides may unintentionally kill other organisms, disrupting the food chain in the local ecosystem.
    e.
        Since the water movement is often faster in the deep sea, any chemicals used in fish farming will be dispersed more quickly over a larger area, so will be less concentrated, which may reduce any inadvertent effect on the local ecosystem.
    f.
        Because they are farther away from land, so any inspection would be more costly and hence likely less frequent; and because the faster waters, deeper sea, and remote location may mean that measuring key markers such as the health and population of local species may be more difficult, and hence less feasible, to monitor. Regulation requires monitoring to be effective.
    g.
        Because they can be fed byproducts of food-crops, which ordinarily could not be sold, so they can be bought for a very low price, so it is less expensive for the fish farmer to feed the fish, lowering operating cost and increasing profit.
    h.
        Because smaller fish farms represent multiple points of failure, and so one accident does not cause as much environmental damage; also, because farmed fish do not need to be transported as far, and transportation releases (amongst other things) carbon dioxide, which is a greenhouse gas which causes global warming as it traps and reflects heat.
