        iii.
            Vomit contains water, which is additional water lost. In addition, vomiting may prevent water which is drunken from being absorbed by the body, as it may be immediately vomited out. This may cause body water content to lower.
            Diarrhoea is faeces which contains much more water than normal. This means more water is lost from the body, so blood concentration may as a result increase.
            High Temperature may induce sweating, which is a loss of water in itself. This means body water content may lower.
    c.
        Body mass is higher in summer than in winter. Water intake in one day is higher in winter than in summer. Urine concentration is higher in summer than in winter.

        Body mass may be higher in the summer because less energy is required in the summer and because food is likely more abundant in the summer. Less energy is required because, as rodents and mammals, degus must be homeotherms, so in the winter must use more energy to maintain their body temperature; in addition, in the winter, plants are likely dead or less available, so it will probably consume less food. Consuming more food and less energy usage means there may be more excess energy to be stored as fat; in contrast, if in the winter the combination of more required energy and less food to consume means the degu consumes less energy as food than it requires, it will burn stored fat to release energy, causing a reduction in bodily mass. However, the change in bodily mass between winter and summer is not very drastic, so this may not be a very severe effect.

        Water intake is likely higher in the winter because there is more water for the degu to intake. This is because more rain falls, so more water can be taken up by plants and so when the degu eats the plants it gets more water. This is in contrast to the summer, where almost no rainfall occurs, so plants slowly dry out, so for roughly the same consumption of plants the degu gets less water.

        The degu getting less water in the summer also likely leads to the higher urine concentration in the summer than in the winter. This is because urine becomes more concentrated as water is reabsorbed out of the collecting duct, and more water is reabsorbed when blood concentration is high, and that is high when there is less water in the body. A combination of more water usage due to the summer heat and the much lower intake of water means that more water will need to be reabsorbed via osmosis out of the collecting duct, so the urine concentration must be higher.
