        iii.
            When a person enters a cold environment, temperature sensors in the skin detect the change in temperatures and send a signal to the hypothalamus. The hypothalamus in turn sends signals via motor neurons to effectors, causing vasoconstriction, hair to stand up (in animals which have hair on their skin), cessation of sweating, and shivering. Vasoconstriction is when sphincter muscles surrounding arterioles in the skin constrict, causing blood to flow through deeper vessels, reducing heat loss. Hair stands up to trap air as insulation, again reducing heat loss. Sweating is a method to shed excess heat; here, that is not necessary, so that stops, reducing heat loss. Shivering is the rapid contraction and relaxation of muscles, which generates heat energy.
    b.
        For both young and old, an increase in heat strain is correlated with an increase in mean skin temperature in degree and with an increase in mean sweating rate per cm^2 of skin. However, given the same heat strain, it holds that both skin temperature and mean sweating rate per cm^2 of young people is higher than that of old people.

        The reason for the increase in skin temperature when heat strain increases seems obvious: an increase in external temperature means there is a lower temperature gradient between the skin/sweat and the ambient air, so methods of cooling such as sweating etc which rely on that temperature gradient become less effective, so core and skin temperature both increase. As body temperature increases, an increase in rate of sweating is only natural, as the body increases the rate of sweating in order to try to cool the body off more.

        Likely, the lower skin temperature in older people reflects a lower core body temperature, which would also explain the lower mean sweating rate. This is likely because as we age our metabolism slows down, so less heat is produced by our bodies, so even under an increase in external temperature, the older people's body temperature is relatively lower than the young people's, so hence their mean sweating rate, which is governed by body temperature, is not as high; and their mean skin temperature also is not as high.
