    a.
        A Gene is a sequence of three bases that codes for a sequence of amino acids to fold into a protein. The Genome is the entire genetic code of an organism.
    b.
        - DNA helix opens up; hydrogen bonds between the base-pairs break
        - MRNA enters the helix
        - adjacent complementary base pair
        - Polymerase binds the free nucleotides back into a polymer
        - MRNA leaves the DNA through the nuclear pore and brings the genetic information to the ribosomes in the cytoplasm
        - DNA helix zips up again
    c.
        Because this is not a frameshift mutation, so any changes are local;
        Because there might be no change to the resultant protein/because the changes to the resultant protein might be so small that the active site is similar enough to function the same;
        Because the swap might be in non-coding DNA which would likely not affect the sequence of amino acids and hence lead to the same protein and enzyme, so the function does not change
